As for the relative configuration of 8 , the $E$ geometry of $\Delta^{11,12}$ and $\Delta^{13,14}$ was established by the NOE correlation from $\mathrm{H}-13$ to $\mathrm{CH}_{3}-18$ and the coupling constants between $\mathrm{H}-13\left(\delta_{\mathrm{H}} 6.96\right.$, dd, $J=11.2$, $15.3 \mathrm{~Hz})$ and $\mathrm{H}-14\left(\delta_{\mathrm{H}} 6.13, \mathrm{~d}, J=15.3 \mathrm{~Hz}\right)$ (Table 1). On the basis of the large coupling constant of $\mathrm{H}-5$ $\left(\delta_{\mathrm{H}} 1.90, \mathrm{dd}, J=12.7,1.1 \mathrm{~Hz}\right)$, the proton of $\mathrm{H}-5$ was determined as an axial orientation. The correlations from $\mathrm{H}-6 \beta$ to $\mathrm{H}-5$ and $\mathrm{H}-7$ in the NOESY spectrum defined the cis-configuration of $\mathrm{H}-5$ and $\mathrm{H}-7$ (Figure 3). Additionally, the $\mathrm{H}_{3}-17$ correlated with $\mathrm{H}-6 \alpha$, which confirmed the trans-configuration between $\mathrm{CH}_{3}-17$ and $\mathrm{H}-5$ (Figure 3). The relative configuration of the C-5, C-7, and C-10 in 8 was thus confirmed as $S^{*}, S^{*}, S^{*}$, respectively.

