Sinulacetate (9) was obtained as a colorless oil. An (+)-HR-EIMS data analysis of 9 indicated the molecular formula $\mathrm{C}_{24} \mathrm{H}_{34} \mathrm{O}_{4}$, which suggested the presence of eight degrees of unsaturation. By inspection of the ${ }^{13} \mathrm{C}$ and ${ }^{1} \mathrm{H}$ NMR spectra, the presence of two acetoxyl groups was immediately recognized $\left(\delta_{\mathrm{C}} 169.8\right.$ and $170.5$, respectively). Eight carbon signals in the downfield implied the occurrence of four double bonds in the molecule, including one terminal $\mathrm{sp}^{2}$ methylene $\left(\delta_{\mathrm{C}} 113.3\right)$. The remaining two degrees of unsaturation were due to the presence of two fused rings in 9. Detailed analysis of the ${ }^{1} \mathrm{H}-{ }^{1} \mathrm{H}$ COSY spectrum of 9 readily characterized three coupling systems (a-c) (Figure 2) by the strong correlations of $\mathrm{H}-2 / \mathrm{H}-3 / \mathrm{H}-7 / \mathrm{H}_{2}-6 / \mathrm{H}-5, \mathrm{H}_{2}-9 / \mathrm{H}_{2}-10 / \mathrm{H}-11$, and $\mathrm{H}-13 / \mathrm{H}-14$, respectively. The key HMBC correlations from $\mathrm{H}_{3}-18$ to $\mathrm{C}-3 / \mathrm{C}-5, \mathrm{H}-7$ to $\mathrm{C}-2 / \mathrm{C}-3 / \mathrm{C}-8 / \mathrm{C}-19, \mathrm{H}_{2}-19$ to C-8/C-9, $\mathrm{H}_{2}-10$ to C-12, H-11 to C-20/C-13, $\mathrm{H}_{3}-20$ to C-11/C-12/C-13, H-14 to C-1/C-13/C-12, H-15 to C-1/C-2/C-14, and $\mathrm{H}_{3}-16 / \mathrm{H}_{3}-17$ to $\mathrm{C}-15 / \mathrm{C}-1$ confirmed the connections of these coupling systems. In view of the above evidences, 9 belongs to a capnosane-type of diterpenoids. Further analysis of the HMBC crosspeaks from $\mathrm{H}-13$ to the carbonyl group at $\delta_{\mathrm{C}} 169.8$ and $\mathrm{H}-14$ to the carbonyl at $\delta_{\mathrm{C}} 170.5$ indicated that the acetoxyl acetate groups were on C-14 and C-13, respectively. Table 1. ${ }^{1} \mathrm{H}(500 \mathrm{MHz})$ and ${ }^{13} \mathrm{C}(125 \mathrm{MHz})$ NMR data $(\delta$ in ppm