The relative stereochemistry of 9 was deduced by analysis of the NMR data and correlations from ROESY spectra. Correlations from $\mathrm{H}_{2}-10$ to $\mathrm{CH}_{3}-20$ and from $\mathrm{H}-2$ to $\mathrm{CH}_{3}-16$ in the ROESY spectrum confirmed the $E$ geometry of $\Delta^{11,12}$ and the $Z$ geometry of $\Delta^{1,2}$ in 9 . A typical triplet with $J_{\mathrm{H}-\mathrm{H}}$ values of $9.5 \mathrm{~Hz}$ of $\mathrm{H}-3$ indicated that the dihedral angles between $\mathrm{H}-3$ and $\mathrm{H}-7$ and between $\mathrm{H}-3$ and $\mathrm{H}-2$ were approximately $0^{\circ}$ or $180^{\circ}$. The ROESY correlations from $\mathrm{H}-6 \beta$ to $\mathrm{H}-7$ and from $\mathrm{H}-6 \alpha$ to $\mathrm{H}-3$ implied the trans-configuration of $\mathrm{H}-3$ and $\mathrm{H}-7$. The thans-configuration of $\mathrm{H}-3$ and $\mathrm{H}-7$ in 9 was further confirmed by the similar multiplicity and coupling constants of $\mathrm{H}-3$ and $\mathrm{H}-7$ with those of sarcophytol L (12) [12], as well as the quite different coupling constants from those of trocheliophols $\mathrm{H}$ (13) and I (14) [13] possessing the cis-configuration of H-3 and H-7 (Table 2). The absence of a crosspeak between $\mathrm{H}-3$ and $\mathrm{H}-7$ in the ROESY spectrum in 9 was also consistent with the above conclusion. As for the relative configurations at C-13 and C-14, the similar carbon chemical shift values between 9 (C-13 $\left(\delta_{\mathrm{C}} 77.1\right)$ and C-14 $\left.\left(\delta_{\mathrm{C}} 73.6\right)\right)$ (Table 1$)$ and $11\left(\mathrm{C}-13\left(\delta_{\mathrm{C}} 77.8\right)\right.$ and C-14 $\left.\left(\delta_{\mathrm{C}} 74.2\right)\right)$ together with the similar coupling constants for protons of $9(\mathrm{H}-13,4.95, \mathrm{~d}, J=10.2 \mathrm{~Hz} ; \mathrm{H}-14,6.02, \mathrm{~d}, J=10.2 \mathrm{~Hz})$ and 11 $(\mathrm{H}-13,5.34, \mathrm{~d}, J=10.0 \mathrm{~Hz} ; \mathrm{H}-14,6.15, \mathrm{~d}, J=10.0 \mathrm{~Hz})[14]$ indicated the threo relative stereochemistry at $\mathrm{C}-13$ and $\mathrm{C}-14$ in 9. Key crosspeaks from $\mathrm{H}_{2}-19$ to $\mathrm{H}-7 / \mathrm{H}_{3}-20$ and from $\mathrm{H}-13$ to $\mathrm{H}-2 / \mathrm{H}_{3}-20$ in the ROESY spectrum indicated the same orientation $(\beta)$ of the protons at $\mathrm{H}-7, \mathrm{H}_{2}-19, \mathrm{H}_{3}-20, \mathrm{H}-13$, and $\mathrm{H}-2$ in the three-dimensional (3D) model (Figure 3). The $\alpha$-orientation of $\mathrm{H}-14$ was determined by the strong ROESY correlation from H-3 to H-14 (Figure 3). Thus, the relative configuration of the carbons in 9 was determined as $3 S^{*}, 7 R^{*}, 13 R^{*}, 14 R^{*}$.

